<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<FindBugsFilter xmlns="https://github.com/spotbugs/filter/3.0.0">
  <!--
    Reviewed suppressions (Chapter 16: suppress with a reason, never disable a whole detector).

    This module ships one deliberate counter-example whose defect IS the lesson, so a test can prove
    the injection sink the chapter's SAST rule targets rather than merely assert it. The detectors are
    left fully ENABLED for the rest of the module (the PreparedStatement fix in OrderLookup, the
    externalized-config SecretsResolver, and the SastSecretsGate running path all stay clean); only the
    one named counter-example that core SpotBugs raises at this module's threshold carries a finding,
    suppressed narrowly, with a reason, and pointed at the test that demonstrates it. The finding was
    verified load-bearing (BugInstance size is 1 with this filter empty, 0 with it as below, deterministic
    across runs). Fixing the class — which OrderLookup already does — is the real advice; the suppression
    exists only so the teaching counter-example ships green.

    Note: core SpotBugs (this build's engine) catches the SQL injection sink below. The deeper
    taint-tracing and the crypto/secrets-specific detectors the chapter discusses are FindSecBugs and the
    standalone SAST tools' territory (Semgrep/CodeQL), which are not part of this build's engine; those
    techniques are demonstrated by the illustrative tool configuration (config/semgrep, ci/sast-scan.yml)
    and by tests/prose here. See the module README.
  -->

  <!--
    Injection (OWASP Top 10:2025 Injection, CWE-89). VulnerableOrderLookup.findOrdersByEmail builds its query
    by string concatenation and passes the nonconstant String to Statement.executeQuery, so SpotBugs
    raises SQL_NONCONSTANT_STRING_PASSED_TO_EXECUTE (verified High here, so the suppression is
    load-bearing, not decorative). This is the same source-to-sink flow the chapter's Semgrep rule
    (config/semgrep/java-injection.yml) targets and that SAST taint analysis traces. The finding IS the
    injection lesson, so it is named as an intentional teaching counter-example. Proven by
    SastSecretsTest.Injection#stringConcatenationFoldsTheInputIntoTheQueryText. The fix is the bound '?'
    parameter in OrderLookup.findOrdersByEmail, never this suppression.
  -->
  <Match>
    <Class name="org.acme.sast.VulnerableOrderLookup"/>
    <Method name="findOrdersByEmail"/>
    <Bug pattern="SQL_NONCONSTANT_STRING_PASSED_TO_EXECUTE"/>
  </Match>
</FindBugsFilter>
